children.text: To polish or not to polish

Thanks to your pregnancy hormones, your nails may have never looked better. Increased levels of estrogen and progesterone may make your nails stronger and grow faster. You may want to take advantage of your newfound nails with a manicure or pedicure. If getting a mani or pedi sounds like a nice way to treat yourself, you’re in luck. Both are considered safe during pregnancy. Whether you are getting your nails done professionally or are more of a do it yourself kind of girl, make sure the area you’re in is well ventilated. A few of the chemicals in nail polish including toluene and formaldehyde can irritate your eyes and throat, so avoid breathing them in as much as possible. Plus, the fumes may make you a bit queasy, especially if you have been fighting morning sickness. To decrease exposure to irritating chemicals, consider only having your nails done once a week or less. Keep in mind, there are also formaldehyde free products on the market, which may be something to consider. As far as acrylic nails, there are few if any studies on their safety in pregnancy. But since there are chemicals involved in applying and filling acrylic nails, you may want to skip the tips until after your baby is born.

You need several key nutrients during pregnancy and vitamin B6 is one of them. Both you and your baby benefit from recommended levels of this water-soluble B vitamin. For example, vitamin B6 helps convert the carbs you eat into energy. It also metabolizes protein and fats for cell building. But it’s not only an important nutrient for you. Vitamin B6 is needed for the proper development of your baby’s brain and nervous system. Luckily, there are a lot of foods rich in vitamin B6 including whole grains, sweet potatoes, chicken, eggs and bananas. If you are concerned you are not eating enough vitamin B-rich foods, your prenatal vitamin likely contains the recommended amount. One thing, which may surprise you about vitamin B6 is it may help reduce nausea and vomiting in some women, although doctors are not sure why it helps. But don’t start taking high doses of vitamin B6 to try to cure morning sickness without talking to your doctor. Like many things in life, you can get too much of a good thing. An overdose of vitamin B6 in the first 12 weeks of pregnancy could harm your developing baby.

Even if you are happy to be pregnant, you may have moments of anxiety and doubt. Some days you might just be downright cranky. If one minute you’re tearing up over a diaper commercial and the next you’re yelling at your dog, you’re probably experiencing mood swings. Mood swings are natural during pregnancy. Between hormonal changes, common pregnancy aches and a little apprehension about labor, pregnancy can be a bit of an emotional roller-coaster. It’s also normal to worry about your parenting skills and how a baby may affect your relationship with your partner. But rest assured you’re not going crazy. Experiencing a range of emotions in pregnancy is common. After all, motherhood is a big transition. It may help to talk to your partner about how you are feeling. Talking things over may prevent him from taking things personally if you are a little irritable at times. Who knows, he may open up about his feelings too, which may help you both feel better. If worry or anxiety is becoming overwhelming or you are feeling depressed, talk with your healthcare provider or a therapist. Discussing your feelings with a professional may help you find ways to work through them.
